  "title": "Epistemic Opacity",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "71ed6ea485baa992",
      "text": "Scientific software is different from lab equipment. [https://blog.khinsen.net/posts/2018/05/07/scientific-software-is-different-from-lab-equipment/ post]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "a438f8a301fcb397",
      "text": "> The overarching issue is that performing a computation by hand, step by step, on concrete data, yields a level of understanding and awareness of potential pitfalls that cannot be achieved by reasoning more abstractly about algorithms. As one moves up the ladder of abstraction from manual computation via writing code from scratch, writing code that relies on libraries, and running code written by others, to having code run by a graduate student, more and more aspects of the computation fade from a researcher’s attention. While a certain level of *epistemic opacity* is inevitable if we want to delegate computations to a machine, there are also many sources of accidental epistemic opacity that can and should be eliminated in order to make scientific results as understandable as possible."
    },
